 with men for restoring Spain’s power in Europe and elsewhere. The collection also includes examples of Guevara’s shorter writings that exemplify her ability to speak on matters of state, network with dignitaries, and govern family affairs. Witty, ironic, and rhetorically sophisticated, Guevara’s essays provide a fresh perspective on the possibilities for women in the public sphere in seventeenth-century Spain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aWomenzSpainxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  abilingual, spanish, academic, scholarly, translation, college, university, textbook, professor, teacher, classroom, student, educational, higher ed, history, historical, aristocratic, aristocrat, essay, protest, corruption, politics, political, womens issues, women, court, portugal, spain, polemics, power, europe, european, 17th century, rhetoric.1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomero-Díaz, Nieves.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226140827423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226140827/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles